-- Air China, BYD, China Rail, Uni-President China: Hong Kong Equity Preview
-- Anna Kitanaka
-- 2010-04-27T00:41:39Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-27/air-china-byd-china-rail-uni-president-china-hong-kong-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  
 The Hang Seng Index rose 1.6 percent to 21,587.06. The Hang
Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, advanced 1.8 percent to 12,380.71  
 China’s coal producers: China’s benchmark coal in
Qinhuangdao port rose to 700-710 yuan a metric ton as of
yesterday from 685-695 yuan on April 19, the China Coal
Transport and Distribution Association said on its Web
site. China Shenhua Energy Co. (1088 HK), the nation’s largest
coal producer, rose 2.8 percent to HK$35.40. China Coal Energy
Co. (1898 HK), the second largest, gained 2.9 percent to
HK$12.18.  
 Air China Ltd. (753 HK): China’s largest international
carrier said it will boost capital expenditure by more than 50
percent in 2010 from a year earlier as it takes delivery of
aircraft to meet a surge in travel demand. The shares increased
4 percent to HK$8.64.  
 BYD Co. (1211 HK): The Chinese carmaker backed by Warren
Buffett said first-quarter profit more than tripled to 1.7
billion yuan ($249 million) on higher demand for vehicles in the
world’s biggest automobile market. The stock advanced 5.6
percent to HK$74.95.  
 China Railway Construction Corp. (1186 HK): The nation’s
biggest railroad builder said first-quarter net income rose 47
percent from a year earlier to 1.4 billion yuan. Sales gained 37
percent to 70 billion yuan, the company said. The shares gained
4.3 percent to HK$9.88.  
 China Railway Group Ltd. (390 HK): The company said profit
attributable to owners of the company for the year ended Dec. 31
rose to 6.89 billion yuan. The stock rose 2.4 percent to HK$5.62.  
 Stella International Holdings Ltd. (1836 HK): The footwear
maker and retailer with outlets in China said first quarter
revenue was $244.7 million, 12 percent more than the same period
a year earlier, citing a recovery in exports. The shares
declined 0.4 percent to HK$15.64.  
 Weichai Power Co. (2338 HK): The Chinese maker of diesel
engines reported net income rose 77 percent to 3.4 billion yuan
on sales of 35.26 billion yuan. The stock rose 2.1 percent to
HK$69.10.  
 Uni-President China Holdings Ltd. (220 HK): The mainland
Chinese unit of Taiwan’s biggest food supplier was cut to
“underweight” from “neutral” by JPMorgan Chase & Co. The
shares declined 4.1 percent to HK$4.88.  
